Currently, ten mounds are identified, including two keyhole-shaped mounds and eight round mounds. It is believed that the site originally consisted of over 14 mounds.{{Sfn|Aso City Bulletin December 2007|2007|p=23}}{{Sfn|Research on Nagamezuka Kofun|2014|pp=11-22}} The main mound, Nagamezuka, measures 111.5 meters in length, making it one of the largest keyhole-shaped mounds in Kumamoto Prefecture, along with the {{ill|Ōno-no-Iwa Kofun|ja|大野窟古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōno-no-Iwa Kofun|qq=}} in {{ill|Hikawa Town|ja|氷川町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hikawa Town|qq=}}, which measures 123 meters. Excavations at Nagamezuka revealed a stone chamber, human bones, and burial artifacts. The site is estimated to date back to the 5th to 6th centuries.{{Sfn|Aso City Bulletin December 2007|2007|p=23}} Some theories associate the Nakadoori Kofuns with the tombs of the {{ill|Aso Clan|ja|阿蘇氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aso Clan|qq=}}, who historically ruled the Aso region.{{Sfn|Nakadoori Kofuns (Heibonsha)|1985}}{{Sfn|Aso City Bulletin December 2007|2007|p=23}}.

The Kofuns were designated a Kumamoto Prefectural Historic Site in 1959 (Showa 34), and the artifacts from Nagamezuka were designated as Kumamoto Prefectural Important Cultural Properties in 2019 (Heisei 31).{{Sfn|Cultural Properties List}} Nearby, the {{ill|Aso Shrine|ja|阿蘇神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aso Shrine|qq=}} and {{ill|Kunizo Shrine|ja|国造神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunizo Shrine|qq=}}, related to the Aso Clan, are also notable sacred sites.

== Excavation History ==
* **1903 (Meiji 36):** Research by Nakamura Tokugorō reported in the Kyūshū Nichinichi Shimbun.{{Sfn|Research on Nagamezuka Kofun|2014|pp=11-22}}
* **1924 (Taishō 13):** Further research by Nakamura Tokugorō published in ''Rekishi Chiri''.{{Sfn|Research on Nagamezuka Kofun|2014|pp=11-22}}
* **1949–1950 (Showa 24–25):** Preliminary surveys and excavations during the Higashidake River improvement project.{{Sfn|Research on Nagamezuka Kofun|2014|pp=11-22}}
* **1959 (Showa 34):** Designation as a Kumamoto Prefectural Historic Site.{{Sfn|Cultural Properties List}}
* **1973 (Showa 48):** Discovery of a pit-style stone chamber near Kurazuka A Mound during land improvement works.{{Sfn|Research on Nagamezuka Kofun|2014|pp=11-22}}
* **1989 (Heisei 1):** Survey by Kumamoto University.{{Sfn|Research on Nagamezuka Kofun|2014|pp=11-22}}
* **2007 (Heisei 19):** Nagamezuka artifacts designated as Aso City Tangible Cultural Properties.
* **2010–2013 (Heisei 22–25):** Reanalysis and reorganization of Nagamezuka artifacts by Kumamoto University.{{Sfn|Research on Nagamezuka Kofun|2014|pp=11-22}}
* **2019 (Heisei 31):** Designation of Nagamezuka artifacts as Kumamoto Prefectural Important Cultural Properties.{{Sfn|Cultural Properties List}}

